**== (reference equality):** compares whether two variables point to the exact same object in memory. For primitives (int, boolean, etc.) it compares values directly since they are not objects.

**equals() (logical equality):** an overridable method on Object that compares content. String, Integer, and all value types override it to compare by value.

```java
String a = new String("hello");
String b = new String("hello");
a == b        // false — different objects
a.equals(b)   // true  — same content

// String pool interning:
String x = "hello";
String y = "hello";
x == y        // true — same interned literal (implementation detail, avoid relying on)
```

**Gotcha:** null.equals() throws NPE. Prefer Objects.equals(a, b) which handles null safely. Always override hashCode() when you override equals() — the contract requires equal objects to have equal hash codes.

**Comparable<T>:** implemented by the class itself. Defines the single 'natural order'. Used by Collections.sort() and TreeSet/TreeMap by default.

```java
class Employee implements Comparable<Employee> {
    @Override
    public int compareTo(Employee other) {
        return Integer.compare(this.id, other.id); // natural order = by id
    }
}
```

**Comparator<T>:** external, reusable strategy. Multiple comparators can exist for the same type.

```java
// Comparator chaining (Java 8+)
Comparator<Employee> byNameThenAge =
    Comparator.comparing(Employee::getName)
              .thenComparingInt(Employee::getAge);

list.sort(byNameThenAge);
```

**When to use which:** Implement Comparable when there's one obvious natural order (e.g. Integer, String). Use Comparator for secondary sorts, sorting you don't own, or ad-hoc ordering.

ArrayList and most collections maintain a `modCount` counter that increments on structural changes (add/remove). The Iterator created by for-each captures modCount at creation and checks it on each call to next(). Any add/remove during iteration causes a mismatch → ConcurrentModificationException.

**Safe alternatives:**
```java
// 1. Iterator.remove() — safe removal during iteration
Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
while (it.hasNext()) {
    if (it.next().startsWith("A")) it.remove(); // OK
}

// 2. removeIf() — cleanest for conditional removal
list.removeIf(s -> s.startsWith("A"));

// 3. Collect to new list
List<String> filtered = list.stream()
    .filter(s -> !s.startsWith("A"))
    .collect(toList());

// 4. CopyOnWriteArrayList — for concurrent access (no CME)
```

**Note:** CopyOnWriteArrayList never throws CME (iterates over a snapshot) but has O(n) write cost.

Method references are shorthand for lambdas that call a single method. They improve readability but have the same semantics.

```java
// 1. Static method reference: ClassName::staticMethod
list.stream().map(Integer::parseInt)   // same as s -> Integer.parseInt(s)
list.stream().forEach(System.out::println)

// 2. Instance method of a particular object: instance::method
String prefix = "Hello";
list.stream().filter(prefix::equals)   // same as s -> prefix.equals(s)

// 3. Instance method of arbitrary instance of a type: ClassName::instanceMethod
list.stream().map(String::toUpperCase) // same as s -> s.toUpperCase()
list.stream().sorted(String::compareTo)

// 4. Constructor reference: ClassName::new
Stream.generate(ArrayList::new)        // same as () -> new ArrayList<>()
list.stream().map(Person::new)         // same as name -> new Person(name)
```

**The functional interface determines which overload is selected.** If multiple constructors exist, the type context picks the right one.

**How parallelStream works:** splits the source into sub-tasks using the Spliterator, processes them on ForkJoinPool.commonPool() threads, then merges results.

**When parallel IS faster:**
- Large dataset (rule of thumb: 10 000+ elements)
- CPU-bound, non-blocking computation per element
- Elements are independently processable (no shared mutable state)
- Source has good split characteristics (ArrayList splits well; LinkedList splits poorly)

**When parallel is SLOWER or WRONG:**
```java
// ❌ Too small — threading overhead exceeds gain
List.of(1,2,3).parallelStream().map(x -> x * 2).toList();

// ❌ Shared mutable state — race conditions
List<String> results = new ArrayList<>();
list.parallelStream().forEach(results::add); // data races!

// ❌ I/O bound — threads just wait, no speedup
list.parallelStream().map(url -> httpClient.get(url));

// ✅ CPU-bound, large, independent
largeList.parallelStream()
    .map(img -> heavyImageProcess(img))
    .collect(toList()); // safe — collect is thread-aware
```

**Always benchmark** before switching to parallel — measure with JMH on production-sized data.
